# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: ribosome
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:ribosome/16s-ribosomal-rna] The genes coding for it are referred to as **16S rRNA genes** and are used in reconstructing phylogenies, due to the slow rates of evolution of this region of the gene.
[src:ribosome/16s-ribosomal-rna] Fox were two of the people who pioneered the use of 16S rRNA in phylogenetics in 1977.
[src:ribosome/16s-ribosomal-rna] Multiple sequences of the 16S rRNA gene can exist within a single bacterium.
[src:ribosome/16s-ribosomal-rna] The descriptor *16S* refers to the size of these ribosomal subunits as reflected indirectly by the speed at which they sediment when samples are centrifuged.
[src:ribosome/16s-ribosomal-rna] The 16S rRNA gene is used for phylogenetic studies as it is highly conserved between different species of bacteria and archaea.
[src:ribosome/16s-ribosomal-rna] Carl Woese pioneered this use of 16S rRNA in 1977.
[src:ribosome/16s-ribosomal-rna] It is suggested that 16S rRNA gene can be used as a reliable molecular clock because 16S rRNA sequences from distantly related bacterial lineages are shown to have similar functionalities.
[src:ribosome/16s-ribosomal-rna] Some thermophilic archaea (e.g. order Thermoproteales) contain 16S rRNA gene introns that are located in highly conserved regions and can impact the annealing of "universal" primers.
[src:ribosome/16s-ribosomal-rna] Mitochondrial and chloroplastic rRNA are also amplified.
[src:ribosome/16s-ribosomal-rna] The most common primer pair was devised by Weisburg *et al.* (1991) and is currently referred to as 27F and 1492R; however, for some applications shorter amplicons may be necessary, for example for 454 sequencing with titanium chemistry the primer pair 27F-534R covering V1 to V3.
[src:ribosome/16s-ribosomal-rna] The two primers are almost identical, but 27F has an M instead of a C.
[src:ribosome/16s-ribosomal-rna] AGAGTTTGATC**M**TGGCTCAG compared with 8F.
[src:ribosome/16s-ribosomal-rna] In addition to highly conserved primer binding sites, 16S rRNA gene sequences contain hypervariable regions that can provide species-specific signature sequences useful for identification of bacteria.
[src:ribosome/16s-ribosomal-rna] As a result, 16S rRNA gene sequencing has become prevalent in medical microbiology as a rapid and cheap alternative to phenotypic methods of bacterial identification.
[src:ribosome/16s-ribosomal-rna] Although it was originally used to identify bacteria, 16S sequencing was subsequently found to be capable of reclassifying bacteria into completely new species, or even genera.
[src:ribosome/16s-ribosomal-rna] It has also been used to describe new species that have never been successfully cultured.
[src:ribosome/16s-ribosomal-rna] With third-generation sequencing coming to many labs, simultaneous identification of thousands of 16S rRNA sequences is possible within hours, allowing metagenomic studies, for example of gut flora.
[src:ribosome/16s-ribosomal-rna] In samples collected from patients with confirmed infections, 16S rRNA next-generation sequencing (NGS) demonstrated enhanced detection in 40% of cases compared to traditional culture methods; moreover, pre-sampling antibiotic consumption did not significantly affect the sensitivity of 16S NGS.
[src:ribosome/16s-ribosomal-rna] The bacterial 16S gene contains nine hypervariable regions (V1–V9), ranging from about 30 to 100 base pairs long, that are involved in the secondary structure of the small ribosomal subunit.
[src:ribosome/16s-ribosomal-rna] The degree of conservation varies widely between hypervariable regions, with more conserved regions correlating to higher-level taxonomy and less conserved regions to lower levels, such as genus and species.
[src:ribosome/16s-ribosomal-rna] While the entire 16S sequence allows for comparison of all hypervariable regions, at approximately 1,500 base pairs long it can be prohibitively expensive for studies seeking to identify or characterize diverse bacterial communities.
[src:ribosome/16s-ribosomal-rna] These studies commonly utilize the Illumina platform, which produces reads at rates 50-fold and 12,000-fold less expensive than 454 pyrosequencing and Sanger sequencing, respectively.
[src:ribosome/16s-ribosomal-rna] While cheaper and allowing for deeper community coverage, Illumina sequencing only produces reads 75–250 base pairs long (up to 300 base pairs with Illumina MiSeq), and has no established protocol for reliably assembling the full gene in community samples.
[src:ribosome/16s-ribosomal-rna] Full hypervariable regions can be assembled from a single Illumina run, however, making them ideal targets for the platform.
[src:ribosome/16s-ribosomal-rna] While 16S hypervariable regions can vary dramatically between bacteria, the 16S gene as a whole maintains greater length homogeneity than its eukaryotic counterpart (18S ribosomal RNA), which can make alignments easier.
[src:ribosome/16s-ribosomal-rna] Additionally, the 16S gene contains highly conserved sequences between hypervariable regions, enabling the design of universal primers that can reliably produce the same sections of the 16S sequence across different taxa.
[src:ribosome/16s-ribosomal-rna] Although no hypervariable region can accurately classify all bacteria from domain to species, some can reliably predict specific taxonomic levels.
[src:ribosome/16s-ribosomal-rna] Many community studies select semi-conserved hypervariable regions like the V4 for this reason, as it can provide resolution at the phylum level as accurately as the full 16S gene.
[src:ribosome/16s-ribosomal-rna] While lesser-conserved regions struggle to classify new species when higher order taxonomy is unknown, they are often used to detect the presence of specific pathogens.
[src:ribosome/16s-ribosomal-rna] In one study by Chakravorty et al. in 2007, the authors characterized the V1–V8 regions of a variety of pathogens in order to determine which hypervariable regions would be most useful to include for disease-specific and broad assays.
[src:ribosome/16s-ribosomal-rna] Amongst other findings, they noted that the V3 region was best at identifying the genus for all pathogens tested, and that V6 was the most accurate at differentiating species between all CDC-watched pathogens tested, including anthrax.
[src:ribosome/16s-ribosomal-rna] While 16S hypervariable region analysis is a powerful tool for bacterial taxonomic studies, it struggles to differentiate between closely related species.
[src:ribosome/16s-ribosomal-rna] In the families *Enterobacteriaceae*, *Clostridiaceae*, and *Peptostreptococcaceae*, species can share up to 99% sequence similarity across the full 16S gene.
[src:ribosome/16s-ribosomal-rna] As a result, the V4 sequences can differ by only a few nucleotides, leaving reference databases unable to reliably classify these bacteria at lower taxonomic levels.
[src:ribosome/16s-ribosomal-rna] By limiting 16S analysis to select hypervariable regions, these studies can fail to observe differences in closely related taxa and group them into single taxonomic units, therefore underestimating the total diversity of the sample.
[src:ribosome/16s-ribosomal-rna] Furthermore, bacterial genomes can house multiple 16S genes, with the V1, V2, and V6 regions containing the greatest intraspecies diversity.
[src:ribosome/16s-ribosomal-rna] While not the most precise method of classifying bacterial species, analysis of the hypervariable regions remains one of the most useful tools available to bacterial community studies.
[src:ribosome/16s-ribosomal-rna] Under the assumption that evolution is driven by vertical transmission, 16S rRNA genes have long been believed to be species-specific, and infallible as genetic markers inferring phylogenetic relationships among prokaryotes.
[src:ribosome/16s-ribosomal-rna] However, a growing number of observations suggest the occurrence of horizontal transfer of these genes.
[src:ribosome/16s-ribosomal-rna] In addition to observations of natural occurrence, transferability of these genes is supported experimentally using a specialized *Escherichia coli* genetic system.
[src:ribosome/16s-ribosomal-rna] Using a null mutant of *E. coli* as host, growth of the mutant strain was shown to be complemented by foreign 16S rRNA genes that were phylogenetically distinct from *E. coli* at the phylum level.
[src:ribosome/16s-ribosomal-rna] Such functional compatibility was also seen in *Thermus thermophilus*.
[src:ribosome/16s-ribosomal-rna] Furthermore, in *T. thermophilus*, both complete and partial gene transfer was observed.
[src:ribosome/16s-ribosomal-rna] Partial transfer resulted in spontaneous generation of apparently random chimera between host and foreign bacterial genes.
[src:ribosome/16s-ribosomal-rna] Thus, 16S rRNA genes may have evolved through multiple mechanisms, including vertical inheritance and horizontal gene transfer; the frequency of the latter may be much higher than previously thought.
[src:ribosome/16s-ribosomal-rna] The 16S rRNA gene is used as the standard for classification and identification of microbes, because it is present in most microbes and shows proper changes.
[src:ribosome/16s-ribosomal-rna] Type strains of 16S rRNA gene sequences for most bacteria and archaea are available on public databases, such as NCBI.
[src:ribosome/16s-ribosomal-rna] However, the quality of the sequences found on these databases is often not validated.
[src:ribosome/16s-ribosomal-rna] Therefore, secondary databases that collect only 16S rRNA sequences are widely used.
[src:ribosome/16s-ribosomal-rna] SILVA provides comprehensive, quality checked and regularly updated datasets of aligned small (16S/18S, SSU) and large subunit (23S/28S, LSU) ribosomal RNA (rRNA) sequences for all three domains of life as well as a suite of search, primer-design and alignment tools (Bacteria, Archaea and Eukarya).
[src:ribosome/16s-ribosomal-rna] GreenGenes is a quality controlled, comprehensive 16S rRNA gene reference database and taxonomy based on a *de novo* phylogeny that provides standard operational taxonomic unit sets.
[src:ribosome/16s-ribosomal-rna] EzBioCloud database, formerly known as EzTaxon, consists of a complete hierarchical taxonomic system containing 62,988 bacteria and archaea species/phylotypes which includes 15,290 valid published names as of September 2018.
[src:ribosome/16s-ribosomal-rna] Based on the phylogenetic relationship such as maximum-likelihood and OrthoANI, all species/subspecies are represented by at least one 16S rRNA gene sequence.
[src:ribosome/16s-ribosomal-rna] The EzBioCloud database is systematically curated and updated regularly which also includes novel candidate species.
[src:ribosome/16s-ribosomal-rna] Moreover, the website provides bioinformatics tools such as ANI calculator, ContEst16S and 16S rRNA DB for QIIME and Mothur pipeline.
[src:ribosome/16s-ribosomal-rna] MIMt is a compact non-redundant 16S database for a rapid metagenomic samples identification.
[src:ribosome/16s-ribosomal-rna] It is composed of 48,749 full 16S sequences belonging to 24,626 well classified bacteria and archaea species.
[src:ribosome/16s-ribosomal-rna] All sequences were obtained from complete genomes deposited in NCBI and for each of the sequences full taxonomic hierarchy is provided.
[src:ribosome/16s-ribosomal-rna] It contains no redundancy, so only one representative for each species was considered avoiding same sequences from different strains, isolates or pathovars resulting in a very fast tool for microorganisms identification, compatible with any classification software (QIIME, Mothur, DADA, etc).
[src:ribosome/16s-ribosomal-rna] The Ribosomal Database Project (RDP) was a curated database that offers ribosome data along with related programs and services.
[src:ribosome/16s-ribosomal-rna] The offerings included phylogenetically ordered alignments of ribosomal RNA (rRNA) sequences, derived phylogenetic trees, rRNA secondary structure diagrams and various software packages for handling, analyzing and displaying alignments and trees.
[src:ribosome/16s-ribosomal-rna] Due to its large size the RDP database is often used as the basis for bioinformatic tool development and creating manually curated databases.
[src:ribosome/16s-ribosomal-rna] The RDP server was taken offline in 2023, but the software is still available for download.
[src:ribosome/18s-ribosomal-rna] Along with the 28S and 5.8S rRNA in eukaryotes, the **18S rRNA** was early identified as integral structural element of ribosomes which were first characterized by their sedimentation properties and named according to measured Svedberg units.
[src:ribosome/18s-ribosomal-rna] Given its ubiquitous presence in eukaryotic life, the evolution of the 18S rRNA was soon proposed as marker for phylogenetic studies to resolve the evolution of eukaryotes.
[src:ribosome/18s-ribosomal-rna] The **18S ribosomal RNA** is the structural RNA of the small subunit in the eukaryotic cytoplasmic ribosome.
[src:ribosome/18s-ribosomal-rna] The genomic sequence of the 18S rRNA is organized in a group with the 28S and 5.8S rRNA, separated and flanked by the ITS-1, ITS-2 and ETS spacer regions.
[src:ribosome/18s-ribosomal-rna] These regions of ribosomal DNA (rDNA) are present with several hundred copies in the active genome, clustered in nucleolus organizer regions (NORs).
[src:ribosome/18s-ribosomal-rna] In ribosome biogenesis, these genes are transcribed together by the RNA polymerase I and are processed in the nucleolus structure of the nucleus.
[src:ribosome/18s-ribosomal-rna] The length of the 18S rRNA varies considerably in the eukaryotic phylogenetic tree, corresponding to a range of 16S-19S in Svedberg units, with the average length commonly given as around 2000 nucleotides.
[src:ribosome/18s-ribosomal-rna] The 18S rRNA of humans has a length of 1869 nucleotides.
[src:ribosome/18s-ribosomal-rna] The universal presence of the **18S rRNA** in eukaryotes and generally high degree of conservation in evolution allow the construction of universal primers for DNA amplification by polymerase chain reaction.
[src:ribosome/18s-ribosomal-rna] The possible applications mirror molecular methods involving 16S rRNA of prokaryotes.
[src:ribosome/18s-ribosomal-rna] Primers binding in highly conserved regions of the 18S rRNA are an important marker for biodiversity screening, allowing the amplification of unspecified or random targets from environmental samples as well as uncharacterized specimens from collections for DNA sequencing.
[src:ribosome/18s-ribosomal-rna] Subsequent sequence alignment covering the less strictly conserved segments then allows the assignment of a sample to biologic clades.
[src:ribosome/18s-ribosomal-rna] In the case of 18S rRNA, retrieval of DNA is improved by the abundance of repeating sequences of the rDNA within eukaryotic cells, promoting the sensitivity of the analysis.
[src:ribosome/18s-ribosomal-rna] Multiple properties of the genomic sequence of the 18S rRNA have established it as an important marker gene for large-scale phylogenetic analysis and the reconstruction of the metazoan tree of life.
[src:ribosome/18s-ribosomal-rna] The integral role in formation and function of the ribosome is a key cause for its omnipresence in eukaryotic life.
[src:ribosome/18s-ribosomal-rna] Meanwhile, the gene maintains a high degree of conservation under a persistent selective pressure in all living beings, highlighting its potential for comparison between distantly related clades.
[src:ribosome/18s-ribosomal-rna] Early studies utilizing the 18S rRNA sequence constructed the first large-scale phylogenetic trees of the metazoa.
[src:ribosome/18s-ribosomal-rna] Evidence from further studies led to the creation of several important clades, such as the Ecdysozoa and Lophotrochozoa.
[src:ribosome/18s-ribosomal-rna] During the latter part of the 2000s, and with increased numbers of taxa included into molecular phylogenies, however, two problems became apparent.
[src:ribosome/18s-ribosomal-rna] First, there are prevailing sequencing impediments in representatives of certain taxa, such as the mollusk classes Solenogastres and Tryblidia, selected bivalve taxa, and the enigmatic crustacean class Remipedia.
[src:ribosome/18s-ribosomal-rna] Failure to obtain 18S sequences of single taxa is considered a common phenomenon but is rarely ever reported.
[src:ribosome/18s-ribosomal-rna] Secondly, in contrast to initially high hopes, 18S cannot resolve nodes at all taxonomic levels and its efficacy varies considerably among clades.
[src:ribosome/18s-ribosomal-rna] This has been discussed as an effect of rapid ancient radiation within short periods.
[src:ribosome/18s-ribosomal-rna] Multigene analyses are currently thought to give more reliable results for tracing deep branching events in Metazoa but 18S still is extensively used in phylogenetic analyses.
[src:ribosome/2-o-methylation] This modification is able to stabilize the structure of RNA while preventing it from undergoing hydrolysis as the hydroxyl group is replaced.
[src:ribosome/2-o-methylation] A technique was developed based on this property called RiboMethSeq to quantify the amount of modifications existing in a sample of rRNA.
[src:ribosome/2-o-methylation] RNA is a short lived molecule and each of the types vary in its longevity in the cell.
[src:ribosome/2-o-methylation] Ribosomal RNA exists longer in the cell before degradation so utilizing 2'-O-Met would aid in stabilizing its structure.
[src:ribosome/2-o-methylation] The epitranscriptomics of this particular RNA modification occurs post-translation, causing a change in the resulting protein without the DNA being altered.
[src:ribosome/2-o-methylation] Having chemical properties intermediate between RNA and DNA, 2'-*O*-methylation is presumed to have been one of the reactive group of RNA molecules on early Earth that would have given rise to DNA.
[src:ribosome/23s-ribosomal-rna] The **23S** rRNA is a 2,904 nucleotide long (in *E. coli*) component of the large subunit (50S) of the bacterial/archean ribosome and makes up the peptidyl transferase center (PTC).
[src:ribosome/23s-ribosomal-rna] The 23S rRNA is divided into six secondary structural domains titled I-VI, with the corresponding 5S rRNA being considered domain VII.
[src:ribosome/23s-ribosomal-rna] The ribosomal peptidyl transferase activity resides in domain V of this rRNA, which is also the most common binding site for antibiotics that inhibit translation, making it a target for ribosomal engineering.
[src:ribosome/23s-ribosomal-rna] A well-known member of this antibiotic class, chloramphenicol, acts by inhibiting peptide bond formation, with recent 3D-structural studies showing two different binding sites depending on the species of ribosome.
[src:ribosome/23s-ribosomal-rna] Numerous mutations in domains of the 23S rRNA with Peptidyl transferase activity have resulted in antibiotic resistance.
[src:ribosome/23s-ribosomal-rna] 23S rRNA genes typically have higher sequence variations, including insertions and/or deletions, compared to other rRNAs.
[src:ribosome/23s-ribosomal-rna] The eukaryotic homolog of the 23S LSU rRNA is the 28S ribosomal RNA, with a region filled by the 5.8S ribosomal RNA.
[src:ribosome/23s-ribosomal-rna] In general, rRNA has an essential function of peptidyl transferase.
[src:ribosome/23s-ribosomal-rna] The stimulating core of the ribosome plays role in the peptide bond configuration.
[src:ribosome/23s-ribosomal-rna] Both peptidyl-tRNA and aminoacyl-tRNA are important for protein synthesis and transpeptidation response.
[src:ribosome/23s-ribosomal-rna] However, 23S rRNA positions (G2252, A2451, U2506, and U2585) have a significant function for tRNA binding in the P site of the large ribosomal subunit.
[src:ribosome/23s-ribosomal-rna] These modification nucleotides in site P can inhibit peptidyl-tRNA from binding.
[src:ribosome/23s-ribosomal-rna] U2555 modification can also intervene with transferring peptidyl-tRNA to puromycin.
[src:ribosome/23s-ribosomal-rna] Furthermore, the chemical modification of half of these positions G2251, G2253, A2439, and U2584 can not prevent the tRNA binding.
[src:ribosome/23s-ribosomal-rna] Peptidyl-tRNA of 50S subunits which binds to the P site preserve eight positions of 23S rRNA from chemical modification.
[src:ribosome/23s-ribosomal-rna] On the other hand, mutation in 23S rRNA can also have impacts on cell growth.
[src:ribosome/23s-ribosomal-rna] Mutations A1912G, A1919G and Ψ1917C have a powerful growth phenotypes and they prevent translation while mutation A1916G has a simple growth phenotype and it leads to defect in the 50S subunits.
[src:ribosome/23s-ribosomal-rna] The 23S ribosomal RNA is composed of six domains forming a complex network of molecular interactions.
[src:ribosome/23s-ribosomal-rna] A central single-stranded region connects all of the domains through base-pairing of the two halves, forming Helix 26a.
[src:ribosome/23s-ribosomal-rna] Some consider Helix 26a to be Domain 0 due to its action as a central core and compact folding unit.
[src:ribosome/23s-ribosomal-rna] Comparison of 23S and 28S ribosomal RNA sequences across species demonstrate conservation of Helix 26a.
[src:ribosome/23s-ribosomal-rna] Helices continue to provide the support as the backbone of domain architecture.
[src:ribosome/23s-ribosomal-rna] Chloroplast ribosomes from "higher" plants have an additional 4.5S rRNA created by fragmentation of 23S.
[src:ribosome/23s-ribosomal-rna] It is located to the 3' side of 23S in the rRNA operon and corresponds to the 3' end of non-fragmented 23S rRNA.
[src:ribosome/28s-ribosomal-rna] Combined with 5.8S rRNA to the 5' side, it is the eukaryotic nuclear homologue of the prokaryotic 23S and mitochondrial 16S ribosomal RNAs.
[src:ribosome/28s-ribosomal-rna] The genes coding for 28S rRNA are referred to as 28S rDNA.
[src:ribosome/28s-ribosomal-rna] The comparison of the sequences from these genes are sometimes used in molecular analysis to construct phylogenetic trees, for example in protists, fungi, insects, arachnids, tardigrades, and vertebrates.
[src:ribosome/28s-ribosomal-rna] The 28S rRNA is typically 4000–5000 nt long.
[src:ribosome/28s-ribosomal-rna] Some eukaryotes cleave 28S rRNA into two parts before assembling both into the ribosome, a phenomenon termed the "hidden break".
[src:ribosome/30s] The **prokaryotic small ribosomal subunit**, or **30S subunit**, is the smaller subunit of the 70S ribosome found in prokaryotes.
[src:ribosome/30s] It is a complex of the 16S ribosomal RNA (rRNA) and 19 proteins.
[src:ribosome/30s] This complex is implicated in the binding of transfer RNA (tRNA) to messenger RNA (mRNA).
[src:ribosome/30s] The small subunit is responsible for the binding and the reading of the mRNA during translation.
[src:ribosome/30s] The small subunit, both the rRNA and its proteins, complexes with the large 50S subunit to form the 70S prokaryotic ribosome in prokaryotic cells.
[src:ribosome/30s] This 70S ribosome is then used to translate mRNA into proteins.
[src:ribosome/30s] The 30S subunit is an integral part of mRNA translation.
[src:ribosome/30s] It binds three prokaryotic initiation factors: IF-1, IF-2, and IF-3.
[src:ribosome/30s] A portion of the 30S subunit (the 16S rRNA) guides the initiating start codon (5′)-AUG-(3′) of mRNA into position by recognizing the Shine-Dalgarno sequence, a complementary binding site about 8 base pairs upstream from the start codon.
[src:ribosome/30s] This ensures the ribosome starts translation at the correct location.
[src:ribosome/30s] The tightness of the bonding between the Shine-Dalgarno sequence on the mRNA and the 16S rRNA determines how efficiently translation proceeds.
[src:ribosome/30s] Once the 16S rRNA recognizes the mRNA start codon, a special transfer RNA, f-Met-tRNA, binds and protein translation begins.
[src:ribosome/30s] The binding site of the f-Met-tRNA on the 30S ribosomal subunit is called the "D-site" This step is required in order for protein synthesis to occur.
[src:ribosome/30s] Then the large ribosomal subunit will bind and protein synthesis will continue.
[src:ribosome/30s] The binding of the large subunit causes a conformational change in the 70S, which opens another site for protein translation.
[src:ribosome/30s] In order to form the translation complex with the 50S subunit, the 30S subunit must bind IF-1, IF-2, IF-3, mRNA, and f-met-tRNA.
[src:ribosome/30s] Next, the 50S subunit binds and a guanosine triphosphate is cleaved to guanosine diphosphate and inorganic phosphate, thus dissociating the initiation factors and resulting in protein translation.
[src:ribosome/30s] This process is called "initiation" and is the slowest process of translation.
[src:ribosome/30s] The small ribosomal subunit is made up of 16S rRNA and 19 full proteins.
[src:ribosome/30s] There is also one polypeptide chain that consists of 26 amino acids.
[src:ribosome/30s] Conventionally, the rRNA is labeled with "H#" to indicate the helix number in high resolution images.
[src:ribosome/30s] Proteins are labelled "S#" to indicate the different peptides involved in rRNA stabilization.
[src:ribosome/30s] S11 and H45 are located near the Shine-Dalgarno binding site, which is also near the IF-3 binding site.
[src:ribosome/30s] Proteins S3, S4, S5, and S12, along with H18, are located near the channel where mRNA is present in the 30S subunit.
[src:ribosome/30s] The 30S subunit is the target of antibiotics such as tetracycline and gentamicin.
[src:ribosome/30s] These antibiotics specifically target the prokaryotic ribosomes, hence their usefulness in treating bacterial infections in eukaryotes.
[src:ribosome/30s] Tetracycline interacts with H27 in the small subunit as well as binding to the A-site in the large subunit.
[src:ribosome/30s] Puromycin is an inhibitor of ribosomal translation.
[src:ribosome/30s] Pactamycin interrupts the binding in the Shine-Dalgarno binding region in the small subunit, thus disrupting activity.
[src:ribosome/30s] Hygromycin B also interacts with H44 and inhibits the translocation movement that is necessary during protein synthesis.
[src:ribosome/40s] The 40S subunit contains the decoding center which monitors the complementarity of tRNA and mRNA in protein translation.
[src:ribosome/40s] It is the largest component of several translation initiation complexes, including the 43S and 48S preinitiation complexes (PICs), being bound by several eukaryotic initiation factors, including eIF1, eIF1A, and eIF3.
[src:ribosome/40s] The 40S ribosomal subunit is also tightly bound by the HCV IRES to form a binary complex mediate by protein-mRNA and rRNA-mRNA interactions.
[src:ribosome/40s] More information can be found in the articles on the ribosome, the eukaryotic ribosome (80S), and the article on protein translation.
[src:ribosome/40s] The shape of the small subunit can be subdivided into two large segments, the head and the body.
[src:ribosome/40s] Characteristic features of the body include the left and right feet, the shoulder and the platform.
[src:ribosome/40s] The head features a pointed protrusion reminiscent of a bird's beak.
[src:ribosome/40s] The mRNA binds in the cleft between the head and the body, and there are three binding sites for tRNA, the A-site, P-site and E-site (see article on protein translation for details).
[src:ribosome/40s] The core of the 40S subunit is formed by the 18S ribosomal RNA (abbreviated 18S rRNA), which is homologous to the prokaryotic 16S rRNA.
[src:ribosome/40s] This rRNA core is decorated with dozens of proteins.
[src:ribosome/40s] In the figure "Crystal Structure of the Eukaryotic 40S Ribosomal Subunit from *Tetrahymena thermophila*", the ribosomal RNA core is represented as a grey tube and expansion segments are shown in red.
[src:ribosome/40s] Proteins which have homologs in eukaryotes, archaea and bacteria are shown as blue ribbons.
[src:ribosome/40s] Proteins shared only between eukaryotes and archaea are shown as orange ribbons and proteins specific to eukaryotes are shown as red ribbons.
[src:ribosome/40s] The table "40S ribosomal proteins" shows the individual protein folds of the 40S subunit colored by conservation.
[src:ribosome/40s] Proteins which have homologs in eukaryotes, archaea and bacteria (EAB) are shown as blue ribbons.
[src:ribosome/40s] Proteins shared only between eukaryotes and archaea (EA) are shown as orange ribbons and proteins specific to eukaryotes (E) are shown as red ribbons.
[src:ribosome/40s] Eukaryote-specific extensions of conserved proteins, ranging from a few residues or loops to very long alpha helices and additional domains, are highlighted in red.
[src:ribosome/40s] For a details, refer to the article on the eukaryotic ribosome.
[src:ribosome/40s] Historically, different nomenclatures have been used for ribosomal proteins.
[src:ribosome/40s] For instance, proteins have been numbered according to their migration properties in gel electrophoresis experiments.
[src:ribosome/40s] Therefore, different names may refer to homologous proteins from different organism, while identical names not necessarily denote homologous proteins.
[src:ribosome/40s] The table "40S ribosomal proteins" crossreferences the human ribosomal protein names with yeast, bacterial and archaeal homologs.
[src:ribosome/40s] Further information can be found in the ribosomal protein gene database (RPG).
[src:ribosome/ribosome] A **ribosome** (/ˈraɪbəzoʊm, -soʊm/) is a ribonucleoprotein particle found in all cells, both prokaryotic and eukaryotic, responsible for the synthesis of proteins.
[src:ribosome/ribosome] A ribosome functions as a molecular machine in the translation of strands of messenger RNA (mRNA) and production of a protein.
[src:ribosome/ribosome] A ribosome links amino acids together in the order specified by the codons of mRNA molecules to form polypeptide chains.
[src:ribosome/ribosome] A ribosome is made up of a large and a small subunit, each consisting of one or more ribosomal RNA molecules and many ribosomal proteins.
[src:ribosome/ribosome] The ribosomes and associated molecules are also known as the *translational apparatus*.
[src:ribosome/ribosome] Ribosome biogenesis is the process of making ribosomes.
[src:ribosome/ribosome] This is an energy-consuming, dynamic process, requiring the synthesis of around 200 proteins in the processing of ribosomal RNAs and assembling them with ribosomal proteins to make the ribosome's subunits.
[src:ribosome/ribosome] The sequence of RNA that encodes the sequence of the amino acids in a protein is transcribed into a messenger RNA (mRNA) chain.
[src:ribosome/ribosome] Ribosomes bind to the messenger RNA molecules and use the RNA's sequence of nucleotides to determine the sequence of amino acids needed to generate a protein.
[src:ribosome/ribosome] Amino acids are selected and carried to the ribosome by transfer RNA (tRNA) molecules, which enter the ribosome and bind to the messenger RNA chain via an anticodon stem loop.
[src:ribosome/ribosome] For each coding triplet (codon) in the messenger RNA, there is a unique transfer RNA that must have the exact anti-codon match, and carries the correct amino acid for incorporating into a growing polypeptide chain.
[src:ribosome/ribosome] Once the protein is produced, it can then fold to produce a functional three-dimensional structure.
[src:ribosome/ribosome] During translation the synthesis of proteins from their building blocks takes place in four stages: initiation, elongation, termination, and ribosome recycling.
[src:ribosome/ribosome] The start codon in all mRNA molecules has the sequence AUG.
[src:ribosome/ribosome] The stop codon may either be UAA, UAG, or UGA; since there are no tRNA molecules that recognize these codons, the ribosome recognizes that translation is complete.
[src:ribosome/ribosome] When a ribosome finishes reading an mRNA molecule, the two subunits separate and are usually broken up but can be reused.
[src:ribosome/ribosome] Ribosomes are a kind of enzyme, called ribozymes because the catalytic peptidyl transferase activity that links amino acids together is performed by the ribosomal RNA.
[src:ribosome/ribosome] Ribosomes from bacteria, archaea, and eukaryotes (in the three-domain system) resemble each other to a remarkable degree, evidence of a common origin.
[src:ribosome/ribosome] They differ in their size, sequence, structure, and the ratio of protein to RNA.
[src:ribosome/ribosome] The differences in structure allow some antibiotics to kill bacteria by inhibiting their ribosomes while leaving human ribosomes unaffected.
[src:ribosome/ribosome] In all domains, a polysome of two or more ribosomes may move along a single mRNA chain at one time, each reading a specific sequence and producing a corresponding protein molecule.
[src:ribosome/ribosome] The mitochondrial ribosomes (mitoribosomes) of eukaryotic cells are distinct from the other ribosomes.
[src:ribosome/ribosome] They functionally resemble those in bacteria, reflecting the evolutionary origin of mitochondria as endosymbiotic bacteria.
[src:ribosome/ribosome] Ribosomes were first observed in the mid-1950s as dense particles or granules by Romanian-American cell biologist George Emil Palade, using an electron microscope.
[src:ribosome/ribosome] They were initially called **Palade granules** due to their granular structure.
[src:ribosome/ribosome] The term "ribosome" was proposed in 1958 by Howard M.
[src:ribosome/ribosome] Albert Claude, Christian de Duve, and George Emil Palade were jointly awarded the Nobel Prize in Physiology or Medicine, in 1974, for the discovery of the ribosome.
[src:ribosome/ribosome] The Nobel Prize in Chemistry 2009 was awarded to Venkatraman Ramakrishnan, Thomas A.
[src:ribosome/ribosome] Yonath for determining the detailed structure and mechanism of the ribosome.
[src:ribosome/ribosome] A ribosome is a ribonucleoprotein particle made from complexes of ribosomal RNAs and proteins, arranged into two ribosomal subunits, one large and the other small.
[src:ribosome/ribosome] Ribosomes are complex molecular machines present in all cells both prokaryotic, and eukaryotic.
[src:ribosome/ribosome] The ribosomal subunits of prokaryotes and eukaryotes are quite similar.
[src:ribosome/ribosome] A ribosome is largely made up of specialized non-coding ribosomal RNA (rRNA) as well as dozens of distinct ribosomal proteins (the number varies slightly between species).
[src:ribosome/ribosome] The ribosomal proteins and rRNAs are arranged into two distinct ribosomal subunits one large and one small.
[src:ribosome/ribosome] The subunits fit together locking around a strand of mRNA, and work together to translate the mRNA into a polypeptide chain during protein synthesis.
[src:ribosome/ribosome] Bacterial ribosomes are around 20 nm (200 Å) in diameter and are composed of 65% rRNA and 35% ribosomal proteins.
[src:ribosome/ribosome] Eukaryotic ribosomes are between 25 and 30 nm (250–300 Å) in diameter with an rRNA-to-protein ratio that is close to 1.
[src:ribosome/ribosome] Crystallographic work has shown that there are no ribosomal proteins close to the reaction site for polypeptide synthesis.
[src:ribosome/ribosome] The unit of measurement used to describe the ribosomal subunits and the rRNA fragments is the Svedberg unit, a measure of the rate of sedimentation in centrifugation rather than size.
[src:ribosome/ribosome] This accounts for why fragment names do not add up: for example, bacterial 70S ribosomes are made of 50S and 30S subunits.
[src:ribosome/ribosome] Prokaryotes have 70S ribosomes, each consisting of a small (30S) and a large (50S) subunit.
[src:ribosome/ribosome] *E. coli*, for example, has a 16S RNA subunit (consisting of 1540 nucleotides) that is bound to 21 proteins.
[src:ribosome/ribosome] The large subunit is composed of a 5S RNA subunit (120 nucleotides), a 23S RNA subunit (2900 nucleotides) and 31 proteins.
[src:ribosome/ribosome] Affinity label for the tRNA binding sites on the *E. coli* ribosome allowed the identification of A and P site proteins most likely associated with the peptidyltransferase activity; labelled proteins are L27, L14, L15, L16, L2; at least L27 is located at the donor site, as shown by E.
[src:ribosome/ribosome] Additional research has demonstrated that the S1 and S21 proteins, in association with the 3′-end of 16S ribosomal RNA, are involved in the initiation of translation.
[src:ribosome/ribosome] Archaeal ribosomes are conventionally quoted as having similar sizes as the bacterial ribosome, being a 70S ribosome made up from a 50S large subunit and a 30S small subunit.
[src:ribosome/ribosome] The rRNA chains are similarly commonly called 16S, 23S, and 5S, though again few (if any) recent sources have truly measured their sedimentation coefficients.
[src:ribosome/ribosome] However, on the sequence and structual levels, they are much closer to eukaryotic ones than to bacterial ones.
[src:ribosome/ribosome] Every extra ribosomal protein archaea have compared to bacteria has a eukaryotic counterpart, while no such relation applies between archaea and bacteria.
[src:ribosome/ribosome] Eukaryotic cells have 80S ribosomes located in their cytosol, each consisting of a small (40S) and large (60S) subunit.
[src:ribosome/ribosome] Their 40S subunit has an 18S RNA (1900 nucleotides) and 33 proteins.
[src:ribosome/ribosome] The large subunit is composed of a 5S RNA (120 nucleotides), 28S RNA (4700 nucleotides), a 5.8S RNA (160 nucleotides) subunits and 49 proteins.
[src:ribosome/ribosome] During 1977, Czernilofsky published research that used affinity labeling to identify tRNA-binding sites on rat liver ribosomes.
[src:ribosome/ribosome] Several proteins, including L32/33, L36, L21, L23, L28/29 and L13 were implicated as being at or near the peptidyl transferase center.
[src:ribosome/ribosome] In eukaryotes, ribosomes are present in mitochondria (sometimes called mitoribosomes) and in plastids such as chloroplasts (also called plastoribosomes).
[src:ribosome/ribosome] They also consist of large and small subunits bound together with proteins into one 70S particle.
[src:ribosome/ribosome] These ribosomes are similar to those of bacteria and these organelles are thought to have originated as symbiotic bacteria.
[src:ribosome/ribosome] Of the two, chloroplastic ribosomes are closer to bacterial ones than mitochondrial ones are.
[src:ribosome/ribosome] Many pieces of ribosomal RNA in the mitochondria are shortened, and in the case of 5S rRNA, replaced by other structures in animals and fungi.
[src:ribosome/ribosome] In particular, *Leishmania tarentolae* has a minimalized set of mitochondrial rRNA.
[src:ribosome/ribosome] In contrast, plant mitoribosomes have both extended rRNA and additional proteins as compared to bacteria, in particular, many pentatricopetide repeat proteins.
[src:ribosome/ribosome] The cryptomonad and chlorarachniophyte algae may contain a nucleomorph that resembles a vestigial eukaryotic nucleus.
[src:ribosome/ribosome] Eukaryotic 80S ribosomes may be present in the compartment containing the nucleomorph.
[src:ribosome/ribosome] The differences between the bacterial and eukaryotic ribosomes are exploited by pharmaceutical chemists to create antibiotics that can destroy a bacterial infection without harming the cells of the infected person.
[src:ribosome/ribosome] Due to the differences in their structures, the bacterial 70S ribosomes are vulnerable to these antibiotics while the eukaryotic 80S ribosomes are not.
[src:ribosome/ribosome] Even though mitochondria possess ribosomes similar to the bacterial ones, mitochondria are not affected by these antibiotics because they are surrounded by a double membrane that does not easily admit these antibiotics into the organelle.
[src:ribosome/ribosome] A noteworthy counterexample is the antineoplastic antibiotic chloramphenicol, which inhibits bacterial 50S and eukaryotic mitochondrial 50S ribosomes.
[src:ribosome/ribosome] Ribosomes in chloroplasts, however, are different: Antibiotic resistance in chloroplast ribosomal proteins is a trait that has to be introduced as a marker, with genetic engineering.
[src:ribosome/ribosome] The various ribosomes share a core structure, which is quite similar despite the large differences in size.
[src:ribosome/ribosome] Much of the RNA is highly organized into various tertiary structural motifs, for example pseudoknots that exhibit coaxial stacking.
[src:ribosome/ribosome] The extra RNA in the larger ribosomes is in several long continuous insertions, such that they form loops out of the core structure without disrupting or changing it.
[src:ribosome/ribosome] All of the catalytic activity of the ribosome is carried out by the RNA; the proteins reside on the surface and seem to stabilize the structure.
[src:ribosome/ribosome] The general molecular structure of the ribosome has been known since the early 1970s.
[src:ribosome/ribosome] In the early 2000s, the structure has been achieved at high resolutions, of the order of a few ångströms.
[src:ribosome/ribosome] The first papers giving the structure of the ribosome at atomic resolution were published almost simultaneously in late 2000.
[src:ribosome/ribosome] The 50S (large prokaryotic) subunit was determined from the archaeon *Haloarcula marismortui* and the bacterium *Deinococcus radiodurans*, and the structure of the 30S subunit was determined from the bacterium *Thermus thermophilus*.
[src:ribosome/ribosome] These structural studies were awarded the Nobel Prize in Chemistry in 2009.
[src:ribosome/ribosome] In May 2001 these coordinates were used to reconstruct the entire *T. thermophilus* 70S particle at 5.5 Å resolution.
[src:ribosome/ribosome] Two papers were published in November 2005 with structures of the *Escherichia coli* 70S ribosome.
[src:ribosome/ribosome] The structures of a vacant ribosome were determined at 3.5 Å resolution using X-ray crystallography.
[src:ribosome/ribosome] Then, two weeks later, a structure based on cryo-electron microscopy was published, which depicts the ribosome at 11–15 Å resolution in the act of passing a newly synthesized protein strand into the protein-conducting channel.
[src:ribosome/ribosome] The first atomic structures of the ribosome complexed with tRNA and mRNA molecules were solved by using X-ray crystallography by two groups independently, at 2.8 Å and at 3.7 Å.
[src:ribosome/ribosome] These structures allow one to see the details of interactions of the *Thermus thermophilus* ribosome with mRNA and with tRNAs bound at classical ribosomal sites.
[src:ribosome/ribosome] Interactions of the ribosome with long mRNAs containing Shine-Dalgarno sequences were visualized soon after that at 4.5–5.5 Å resolution.
[src:ribosome/ribosome] In 2023, a cryo-electron microscopy study reported a 1.55 Å structure of the *Escherichia coli* 70S ribosome in the translating state, providing near-atomic detail of rRNA modifications, tRNA-mRNA interactions, and ion coordination.
[src:ribosome/ribosome] The high-resolution map enabled identification of ribosomal polymorphism sites and visualization of transient chimeric hybrid states associated with tRNA translocation at approximately 2 Å resolution.
[src:ribosome/ribosome] These findings improved structural understanding of the ribosome's functional regions and offered valuable insights for antibiotic design.
[src:ribosome/ribosome] In 2011, the first complete atomic structure of the eukaryotic 80S ribosome from the yeast *Saccharomyces cerevisiae* was obtained by crystallography.
[src:ribosome/ribosome] The model reveals the architecture of eukaryote-specific elements and their interaction with the universally conserved core.
[src:ribosome/ribosome] At the same time, the complete model of a eukaryotic 40S ribosomal structure in *Tetrahymena thermophila* was published and described the structure of the 40S subunit, as well as much about the 40S subunit's interaction with eIF1 during translation initiation.
[src:ribosome/ribosome] Similarly, the eukaryotic 60S subunit structure was also determined from *Tetrahymena thermophila* in complex with eIF6.
[src:ribosome/ribosome] In addition, high-resolution cryo-EM structures of a thermophilic eukaryotic 80S ribosome captured in two rotational states at ~2.9 Å and ~3.0 Å resolution revealed atomistic details of the eukaryotic translocation mechanism and conformational dynamics of eEF2 during GTP hydrolysis.
[src:ribosome/ribosome] Ribosomes are minute particles consisting of RNA and associated proteins that function to synthesize proteins.
[src:ribosome/ribosome] Proteins are needed for many cellular functions, such as repairing damage or directing chemical processes.
[src:ribosome/ribosome] Ribosomes can be either free, floating within the cytoplasm or attached to the rough endoplasmic reticulum.
[src:ribosome/ribosome] Their main function is to convert genetic code into an amino acid sequence and to build protein polymers from amino acid monomers.
[src:ribosome/ribosome] Ribosomes act as catalysts in two extremely important biological processes called peptidyl transfer and peptidyl hydrolysis.
[src:ribosome/ribosome] In summary, ribosomes have two main functions: Decoding the message, and the formation of peptide bonds.
[src:ribosome/ribosome] These two functions reside in the ribosomal subunits.
[src:ribosome/ribosome] Each subunit is made of one or more rRNAs and many r-proteins.
[src:ribosome/ribosome] The small subunit (30S in bacteria and archaea, 40S in eukaryotes) has the decoding function, whereas the large subunit (50S in bacteria and archaea, 60S in eukaryotes) catalyzes the formation of peptide bonds, referred to as the peptidyl-transferase activity.
[src:ribosome/ribosome] The bacterial (and archaeal) small subunit contains the 16S rRNA and 21 r-proteins (*Escherichia coli*), whereas the eukaryotic small subunit contains the 18S rRNA and 32 r-proteins (Saccharomyces cerevisiae, although the numbers vary between species).
[src:ribosome/ribosome] The bacterial large subunit contains the 5S and 23S rRNAs and 34 r-proteins (*E. coli*), with the eukaryotic large subunit containing the 5S, 5.8S, and 25S/28S rRNAs and 46 r-proteins (*S. cerevisiae*; again, the exact numbers vary between species).
[src:ribosome/ribosome] Ribosomes are the workplaces of protein biosynthesis, the process of translating mRNA into protein.
[src:ribosome/ribosome] The mRNA comprises a series of codons which are decoded by the ribosome to make the protein.
[src:ribosome/ribosome] Using the mRNA as a template, the ribosome traverses each codon (3 nucleotides) of the mRNA, pairing it with the appropriate amino acid provided by an aminoacyl-tRNA.
[src:ribosome/ribosome] Aminoacyl-tRNA contains a complementary anticodon on one end and the appropriate amino acid on the other.
[src:ribosome/ribosome] For fast and accurate recognition of the appropriate tRNA, the ribosome utilizes large conformational changes (conformational proofreading).
[src:ribosome/ribosome] The small ribosomal subunit, typically bound to an aminoacyl-tRNA containing the first amino acid methionine, binds to an AUG codon on the mRNA and recruits the large ribosomal subunit.
[src:ribosome/ribosome] The ribosome contains three RNA binding sites, designated A, P, and E.
[src:ribosome/ribosome] The A-site binds an aminoacyl-tRNA or termination release factors; the P-site binds a peptidyl-tRNA (a tRNA bound to the poly-peptide chain); and the E-site (exit) binds a free tRNA.
[src:ribosome/ribosome] Protein synthesis begins at a start codon AUG near the 5′-end of the mRNA. mRNA binds to the P site of the ribosome first.
[src:ribosome/ribosome] The ribosome recognizes the start codon by using the Shine-Dalgarno sequence of the mRNA in prokaryotes and Kozak box in eukaryotes.
[src:ribosome/ribosome] Although catalysis of the peptide bond involves the C2 hydroxyl of RNA's P-site adenosine in a proton shuttle mechanism, other steps in protein synthesis (such as translocation) are caused by changes in protein conformations.
[src:ribosome/ribosome] Since their catalytic core is made of RNA, ribosomes are classified as "ribozymes," and it is thought that they might be remnants of the RNA world.
[src:ribosome/ribosome] In Figure 5, both ribosomal subunits (small and large) assemble at the start codon (towards the 5' end of the mRNA).
[src:ribosome/ribosome] The ribosome uses tRNA that matches the current codon (triplet) on the mRNA to append an amino acid to the polypeptide chain.
[src:ribosome/ribosome] This is done for each triplet on the mRNA, while the ribosome moves towards the 3' end of the mRNA.
[src:ribosome/ribosome] Usually in bacterial cells, several ribosomes are working parallel on a single mRNA, forming what is called a *polyribosome* or *polysome*.
[src:ribosome/ribosome] The ribosome is known to actively participate in the protein folding.
[src:ribosome/ribosome] The structures obtained in this way are usually identical to the ones obtained during protein chemical refolding; however, the pathways leading to the final product may be different.
[src:ribosome/ribosome] In some cases, the ribosome is crucial in obtaining the functional protein form.
[src:ribosome/ribosome] For example, one of the possible mechanisms of folding of the deeply knotted proteins relies on the ribosome pushing the chain through the attached loop.
[src:ribosome/ribosome] Presence of a ribosome quality control protein Rqc2 is associated with mRNA-independent protein elongation.
[src:ribosome/ribosome] This elongation is a result of ribosomal addition (via tRNAs brought by Rqc2) of ***CAT** tails*: ribosomes extend the ***C***-terminus of a stalled protein with random, translation-independent sequences of ***a***lanines and ***t***hreonines.
[src:ribosome/ribosome] Ribosomes are classified as being either "free" or "membrane-bound".
[src:ribosome/ribosome] Free and membrane-bound ribosomes differ only in their spatial distribution; they are identical in structure.
[src:ribosome/ribosome] Whether the ribosome exists in a free or membrane-bound state depends on the presence of an ER-targeting signal sequence on the protein being synthesized, so an individual ribosome might be membrane-bound when it is making one protein, but free in the cytosol when it makes another protein.
[src:ribosome/ribosome] Ribosomes are sometimes referred to as organelles, but the use of the term *organelle* is often restricted to describing sub-cellular components that include a phospholipid membrane, which ribosomes, being entirely particulate, do not.
[src:ribosome/ribosome] For this reason, ribosomes may sometimes be described as "non-membranous organelles".
[src:ribosome/ribosome] Free ribosomes can move about anywhere in the cytosol, but are excluded from the cell nucleus and other organelles.
[src:ribosome/ribosome] Proteins that are formed from free ribosomes are released into the cytosol and used within the cell.
[src:ribosome/ribosome] Since the cytosol contains high concentrations of glutathione and is, therefore, a reducing environment, proteins containing disulfide bonds, which are formed from oxidized cysteine residues, cannot be produced within it.
[src:ribosome/ribosome] When a ribosome begins to synthesize proteins needed in certain organelles, the ribosome making this protein can become "membrane-bound".
[src:ribosome/ribosome] In eukaryotic cells this happens in a region of the endoplasmic reticulum (ER) called the "rough ER".
[src:ribosome/ribosome] The newly produced polypeptide chains are inserted directly into the ER by the ribosome undertaking vectorial synthesis and are then transported to their destinations, through the secretory pathway.
[src:ribosome/ribosome] Bound ribosomes usually produce proteins that are used within the plasma membrane or are expelled from the cell via *exocytosis*.
[src:ribosome/ribosome] In bacterial cells, ribosomes are synthesized in the cytoplasm through the transcription of multiple ribosome gene operons.
[src:ribosome/ribosome] In eukaryotes, the process takes place both in the cell cytoplasm and in the nucleolus, which is a region within the cell nucleus.
[src:ribosome/ribosome] The assembly process involves the coordinated function of over 200 proteins in the synthesis and processing of the four rRNAs, as well as assembly of those rRNAs with the ribosomal proteins.
[src:ribosome/ribosome] The ribosome may have first originated as a protoribosome, possibly containing a peptidyl transferase centre (PTC), in an RNA world, appearing as a self-replicating complex that only later evolved the ability to synthesize proteins when amino acids began to appear.
[src:ribosome/ribosome] Studies suggest that ancient ribosomes constructed solely of rRNA could have developed the ability to synthesize peptide bonds.
[src:ribosome/ribosome] In addition, evidence strongly points to ancient ribosomes as self-replicating complexes, where the rRNA in the ribosomes had informational, structural, and catalytic purposes because it could have coded for tRNAs and proteins needed for ribosomal self-replication.
[src:ribosome/ribosome] Hypothetical cellular organisms with self-replicating RNA but without DNA are called ribocytes (or ribocells).
[src:ribosome/ribosome] As amino acids gradually appeared in the RNA world under prebiotic conditions, their interactions with catalytic RNA would increase both the range and efficiency of function of catalytic RNA molecules.
[src:ribosome/ribosome] In 1958, Francis Crick famously proposed the "one gene-one ribosome-one protein hypothesis," where each ribosome carries the genetic information required to encode a single protein.
[src:ribosome/ribosome] Certain researchers have suggested that heterogeneity in the composition of ribosomal proteins in mammals is important for gene regulation, *i.e.*, the specialized ribosome hypothesis.
[src:ribosome/ribosome] However, this hypothesis is controversial and the topic of ongoing research.
[src:ribosome/ribosome] Heterogeneity in ribosome composition was first proposed to be involved in translational control of protein synthesis by Vince Mauro and Gerald Edelman.
[src:ribosome/ribosome] They proposed the ribosome filter hypothesis to explain the regulatory functions of ribosomes.
[src:ribosome/ribosome] Evidence has suggested that specialized ribosomes specific to different cell populations may affect how genes are translated.
[src:ribosome/ribosome] Some ribosomal proteins exchange from the assembled complex with cytosolic copies suggesting that the structure of the *in vivo* ribosome can be modified without synthesizing an entire new ribosome.
[src:ribosome/ribosome] Certain ribosomal proteins are absolutely critical for cellular life while others are not.
[src:ribosome/ribosome] In budding yeast, 14/78 ribosomal proteins are non-essential for growth, while in humans this depends on the cell of study.
[src:ribosome/ribosome] Other forms of heterogeneity include post-translational modifications to ribosomal proteins such as acetylation, methylation, and phosphorylation.
[src:ribosome/ribosome] *Arabidopsis*, Viral internal ribosome entry sites (IRESs) may mediate translations by compositionally distinct ribosomes.
[src:ribosome/ribosome] For example, 40S ribosomal units without eS25 in yeast and mammalian cells are unable to recruit the CrPV IGR IRES.
[src:ribosome/ribosome] Heterogeneity of ribosomal RNA modifications plays a significant role in structural maintenance and/or function and most mRNA modifications are found in highly conserved regions.
[src:ribosome/ribosome] The most common rRNA modifications are pseudouridylation and 2'-O-methylation of ribose.
